record_data.record_plain_text: 13.1 Delivery Meters All real and reactive power deliveries shall be metered at the KM Green Substation with meters meeting the requirements of the CAISO Tariff. Any conflicts with regard to metering standards that may arise between this Agreement and the CAISO Tariff shall be resolved consistent with the CAISO Tariff. Power deliveries shall be metered at the voltage described in Section 6.1. At a minimum, the Responsible Meter Party shall meter all power flowing across the Interconnection in both directions. The Parties shall cooperate in the installation and provision of access to the meters, as necessary for each Party to obtain the information needed to perform as contemplated under this Agreement. 13.2 Obligation to Provide Telemetry Data To the extent that either Party provides telemetry data to its Balancing Authority or provides access to the other Party’s Balancing Authority for polling of telemetry data, each Party will grant the other Party access to the same telemetry data. With respect to such data, the receiving Party shall treat the data as confidential, not to be used for merchant purposes, and shall not release the data to a third party except as per Section 10.13 of this agreement.

14.1 Billing and Payment Procedures The Parties shall bill each other for any Costs pursuant to the Agreement. Disputes relating to Costs are to be resolved pursuant to Section 14.4, below. Payments shall be due 30 days after bills are received by the billed Party (“the Payment Due Date”) unless a different due date is selected by mutual written agreement of the Parties. KMPUD shall pay PG&E Costs owed pursuant to this Agreement at: Pacific Gas and Electric CompanyPayment Processing CenterResearch Unit / B5AP.O. Box 770000San Francisco, CA 94177
PG&E shall pay KMPUD Costs owed pursuant to this Agreement at: Kirkwood Meadows Public Utility DistrictPO Box 247Kirkwood, CA 95646 14.2 Interest on Overdue Bills Overdue bills shall accrue interest from the Payment Due Date until the date full payment is made at the rate calculated in accordance with the methodology for refunds pursuant to FERC’s Regulations 18 C.F.R. § 35.19(a), as such regulation may be changed or superseded. 14.3 Adjustments All adjustments, billing errors, or the adjustment of advance or estimated billings to actual shall be resolved promptly, and, upon resolution, shall be included in the next regular billing. Such adjustments shall be subject to the payment and interest calculation provisions of Section 14.2. Interest shall accrue on overpayments or underpayments from the Payment Due Date of the billing statement that was adjusted until the date the adjusted amount is paid at the rate determined by Section 14.2. 14.4 Disputed Amounts PG&E and KMPUD shall endeavor to resolve any billing dispute within thirty (30) calendar days of a Party’s receipt of the other Party’s notice of dispute (or such extended period as the Parties may mutually establish in writing). If the Parties cannot agree, either Party may initiate dispute resolution pursuant to Section 23. Except to the extent the Parties agree otherwise in writing, all settlements of disputed amounts shall be subject to the provisions of Section 14.2. Interest shall accrue pursuant to Section 14.2 from the date the disputed amount was due until the date such settlement is paid.

record_data.record_plain_text: 15.1 Accounting Procedures PG&E and KMPUD each shall record relevant Cost(s) and maintain its accounting records in accordance with generally accepted accounting practices and as to PG&E the FERC Uniform System of Accounts. 15.2 Audit Rights For good cause and upon reasonable notice, each Party shall have the right to audit, at its own expense, the relevant records of the other Party for the limited purpose of determining whether the other Party is meeting its obligations under this Agreement. Such audits shall be limited to only those records reasonably required to determine compliance with this Agreement, and each Party agrees to disclose the information obtained in such audit only to those persons, whether employed by such Party or otherwise, that are directly involved in the administration of this Agreement. Each Party agrees that under no circumstances will it use any information obtained in such an audit for any commercial purpose or for any purpose other than assuring enforcement of this Agreement. The right to audit shall be limited to data for two prior years from the date of the final billing for a matter or from the date of the questioned event, as applicable. In accordance with California Government Code Section 8546.7, the Parties acknowledge that this Agreement, and performance and payments under it, are subject to examination and audit by the State Auditor General for three years following final payment under the Agreement.

record_data.record_plain_text: 10.1 Good Utility Practice and Applicable Requirements Obligation When a Party is required by this Agreement to take action with respect to the planning, design, construction, maintenance, study, operation, or use of, or the making of Modifications, New Facility Additions, or Long-Term Changes to Operations to its Electric System, including the Interconnection Facilities, it shall take such action reasonably and in good faith, and in accordance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Requirements to avoid significantly affecting the operation of the other Party’s Electric System and to avoid or mitigate Adverse Impacts. 10.2 Power Delivery and Quality Standard Power delivered is commonly designated as three phase alternating current, at nominal 60 Hertz, and at the nominal voltage required for each Point of Interconnection. Normal variations in voltage and frequency shall be permitted pursuant to Good Utility Practice. KMPUD shall be solely responsible for installing voltage regulating equipment to meet its own voltage requirements. Furthermore, KMPUD shall operate its Electric System to maintain a balanced 3-phase system. Each Party shall plan, design, and operate its Electric System so as to minimize the interchange of reactive power at Interconnections. 10.3 Coordination of Operations PG&E and KMPUD shall at all times coordinate and communicate their various outages and other switching operations that may have an effect on the operations of the other Party’s Electric System and may reasonably be required to protect the integrity of the Balancing Authority Area during Emergencies. PG&E and KMPUD are also responsible for maintenance and switching operations of their Electric Systems. Either Party, if acting consistent with its requirements to maintain and operate its Electric System in accordance with Good Utility Practice, may from time to time remove various elements of its Electric System from operation or initiate other actions which may affect operations or the transfer of energy across Point of Interconnection without an obligation to reimburse the other Party for costs it may incur as a result. The Parties shall endeavor to coordinate their activities in advance of the operation and maintenance of their Electric Systems in order to avoid or minimize any adverse effects of those activities on each other. In the event KMPUD wishes PG&E to perform switching or other non-capital work activities in support of KMPUD’s operational needs, the Parties will execute a Work Performance Agreement as shown in Exhibit B of the TFA. 10.4 Relationship to Balancing Authority Area Operations PG&E currently operates in the CAISO Balancing Authority Area and once KMPUD’s project is operational, KMPUD will also operate in the CAISO Balancing Authority Area. The Parties shall operate in accordance with Good Utility Practice and in compliance with applicable requirements of federal, state, and local laws, licenses, and permits. In the event that PG&E or KMPUD makes any changes in its relationship with the CAISO, the Party making the change shall, if practical, give as much advance notice, including 30 days’ notice if possible, to the other Party. 10.5 Separate Balancing Authority Area Nothing in this Agreement shall prevent either Party from joining or forming a new Balancing Authority Area. In such event, this Agreement shall be revised as appropriate to reflect such change in Balancing Authority Area operations. 10.6 Reporting Significant Events Each Party shall promptly, after reporting to the Balancing Authority, report to the other Party any Emergency or other significant operating event reasonably likely to affect operation of the other Party’s Electric System at each Point of Interconnection. For notice to PG&E, such notice shall be by telephone to PG&E’s Transmission Operations Center personnel or such other substation or switching center as may be designated by PG&E. For notice to KMPUD, such notice shall be by telephone to KMPUD’s Control Center, or as otherwise designated by KMPUD. KMPUD is responsible for providing a contact phone number that will allow PG&E to reach KMPUD’s operations manager 24-hours a day and 7-days a week. Each Party, upon request and on a case-by-case basis for reasonable cause related to operating conditions, shall, in a timely manner, provide to the other Party Electric System operating information, such as loading on lines and equipment and levels of operating voltages and electric power factors. In the event of interruptions, including power quality events, of electric service at any Point of Interconnection, the Party causing the interruption shall report, in a timely manner if known, to the other Party the nature and suspected cause of the event, actions being taken to restore electric service, and the estimated time until restoration of electric service. 10.7 Operation Pursuant to Good Utility Practice Good Utility Practice shall be the general standard for performance related to Electric System operation by the Parties under this Agreement. Each Party shall plan and operate its respective Electric System in accordance with Good Utility Practice and endeavor to minimize electrical disturbances on the Electric System of the other Party. No Party shall be obligated to operate in a manner contrary to Good Utility Practice. If for any reason KMPUD does not operate in a manner consistent with Good Utility Practice or does not meet the terms and conditions of this Agreement, PG&E will have the right to terminate the Agreement for default pursuant to Section 22.1 and disconnect from KMPUD’s Electric System. This would include removing the cable from the Dam. 10.8 Settlement of Disputes and Arbitration The Parties agree to make best efforts to settle all disputes between the Parties connected with this Agreement as a matter of normal business practice under this Agreement. Any unresolved disputes that cannot be resolved informally shall be resolved through the dispute resolution procedure set forth in Section 23. 10.9 Protective Devices Both Parties shall, consistent with CAISO requirements and Good Utility Practice, install, modify, set and adjust the protective relaying equipment associated with facilities within its respective Electric System. Such settings and adjustments or replacement shall be coordinated. Adjustments or replacement made by either Party to its protective relaying equipment shall be consistent with PG&E’s then-current Transmission Interconnection Handbook, available on-line at http://www.PGE.com. 10.10 General Interconnection Requirements Each Party’s facilities or control equipment at existing and proposed Points of Interconnection between the Parties shall be provided, operated, and maintained by each Party in a manner to ensure the safe and reliable operation of the Parties’ Electric Systems, consistent with Good Utility Practice and CAISO’s operating instructions. In the event that replacement or improvement of facilities described in Sections 7.3.1 and 7.5 meets any of the following criteria: (1) involves reconductoring or rebuilding the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line to a higher capacity; (2) involves reconductoring or rebuilding the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV to a higher voltage; (3) upgrading the protection equipment and/or termination equipment at Salt Springs and/or Tiger Creek; (4) is made on one Party’s side of an Interconnection consistent with Good Utility Practice; or (5) such changes necessitate complementary replacement or improvement of facilities on the other Party’s side of the Interconnection to be consistent with Good Utility Practice; then such necessary changes to the other Party’s facilities shall be made by the other Party at its own expense. In such a case, the initiating Party shall provide a reasonable advance notice of such changes to ensure coordination between the Parties of any planned outages associated with such changes. 10.11 Continuity of Service 10.11.1 Operation Actions to Maintain Continuity Each Party shall take actions that are reasonable and consistent with Balancing Authority Area Arrangements and Good Utility Practice as necessary to maintain continuity of service between the Parties. Such actions may include, but are not limited to, opening or closing circuit breakers or other components of the interconnections. 10.11.2 Unscheduled Interruptions Either Party may temporarily interrupt or reduce any service, or temporarily separate all or any part of the facilities of its Electric System from the other Party’s Electric System to implement CAISO operating orders and their respective Balancing Authority Area Arrangements or Good Utility Practice at any time that: (i) a System Emergency exists, provided that if the unscheduled interruption is not undertaken pursuant to an CAISO operating order (a) such interruption, reduction of service or separation is necessary to remedy the System Emergency, and (b) its duration is as short a time as reasonable under the circumstances; (ii) the action is necessary to prevent a hazard to life or property; or (iii) the operation of the Party’s Electric System is suspended, interrupted or interfered with as a result of an Uncontrollable Force. Reasonable effort shall be made to coordinate any such interruption and such interruption will be immediately communicated to the other Party. In the event of such interruption or reduction in service, the Parties shall restore full service on a basis comparable to the restoration of other public service and safety facilities and consistent with their respective Balancing Authority Area Arrangements. 10.11.3 Scheduled Interruptions All scheduled interruptions of service shall be made as mutually agreed by the Parties and in accordance with Balancing Authority Area Arrangements and Good Utility Practice. Whenever possible, the Parties shall endeavor to give at least 72 hours advance notice of any such interruption, reduction or separation, and its probable duration. 10.11.4 Interruption By Protective Devices PG&E and KMPUD utilize automatic protective devices in order to assist in maintaining the integrity and reliability of their respective Electric Systems and to protect their customers from damage, injury or prolonged outages. Service on the PG&E and KMPUD Electric Systems is subject to interruption in the event of operation of such devices. In the event of such interruption, service will be restored consistent with Good Utility Practice and Balancing Authority Area Arrangements. In addition, PG&E and KMPUD shall coordinate such restoration and all installations, upgrades, and replacements of protective devices at Point of Interconnection in accordance with Good Utility Practice. 10.11.5 Jeopardy If at any time continuity of service within the CAISO Balancing Authority Area is being jeopardized due to failure of facilities, PG&E and/or KMPUD shall coordinate their responses to the jeopardy, to implement CAISO operating orders in accordance with their respective Balancing Authority Area Arrangements, and Good Utility Practice. Such coordination may include the reduction of load; provided, except as otherwise set forth in the Parties’ Balancing Authority Area Arrangements, that such reduction shall maintain, as far as may be practicable, the relative sizes of load served by each Party in the same proportion as existed before such reduction. Either Party may also temporarily interrupt or reduce deliveries to Point of Interconnection or separate all or a part of the facilities of its Electric System from all or a part of the Electric System of the other Party, or the Electric System which directly or indirectly serves the other Party, if the first Party determines that the following conditions exist or that the described action is necessary: (i) a System Emergency; (ii) in order to install equipment on, make repairs or replacements to, make investigations and inspections of, or perform maintenance or other work on PG&E’s Electric System; (iii) to prevent a hazard to life or property; (iv) as necessitated by Good Utility Practice; or (v) where the operation of PG&E’s Electric System is suspended, interrupted or interfered with as a result of Uncontrollable Force. The Parties understand and agree that load curtailment under such circumstances is a matter that should be coordinated among PG&E, KMPUD and the CAISO based upon the CAISO Tariff and any Balancing Authority Area Arrangements entered into between PG&E, KMPUD and the CAISO. 10.12 Operating Records Each Party shall maintain operating records in accordance with Good Utility Practice. Each Party shall have reasonable access to such operating records kept by the other Party which reasonably relate to interconnected operation of the Parties’ Electric Systems; provided, that a Party requesting such records shall be required, to the extent permitted by law, to keep such records confidential if requested to do so by the other Party. Such records shall include, but not be limited to, operating logs, scheduled transfers through each Point of Interconnection, line loadings, outage and power quality reports, voltages and reactive power. 10.13 Mutual Obligation Communications Protocol The Parties shall establish a mutual obligation communications protocol that will cover clear and timely communication between the Parties regarding items such as, but not limited to (a) complying with maintenance schedules that conform to Good Utility Practice, and (b) the reporting of Electric System disturbances. 10.14 Confidentiality The Parties anticipate that during the course of the Parties’ relationship under this Agreement, they will at times supply copies of confidential or proprietary information to each other, including information that should be kept confidential from and not disclosed to certain departments within a Party (e.g. transmission planning information that cannot be disclosed to marketing personnel) or to Third Parties, including the public. If one Party supplies confidential information to the other, it is the responsibility of the supplying Party to inform the receiving Party that such information is confidential and to label or otherwise mark each confidential document or electronic file “CONFIDENTIAL”. It shall be the responsibility and obligation of the receiving Party to maintain the confidentiality of such information in accordance with the supplying Party’s reasonable instructions, and to avoid disclosure of information designated confidential to any Third Party unless required to do so by law. If a Party (“Receiving Party”) receives a request from a Third Party, whether under the California Public Records Act, California Government Code Sections 6250-6270, as amended, or otherwise, for access to, or inspection, disclosure or copying of, any of the other Party’s confidential data or information (“Disclosure Request”), then the Receiving Party shall provide notice to and a copy of the Disclosure Request to the other Party within 3 Business Days of receipt of the Disclosure Request. Within 3 Business Days of receipt of such notice, the other Party shall provide notice to the Receiving Party either: (a) that the other Party believes there are reasonable legal grounds for denying or objecting to the Disclosure Request, and the other Party requests the Receiving Party to deny or object to the Disclosure Request with respect to identified confidential information. In such case, the other Party will either defend the denial of the Disclosure Request at its sole Cost (with reasonable assistance by the Receiving Party), or it shall indemnify the Receiving Party for all reasonable Costs associated with denying or objecting to the Disclosure Request. Such indemnification by the other Party of the Receiving Party shall include all of the Receiving Party’s Costs reasonably incurred with respect to denial of or objection to the Disclosure Request, including but not limited to Costs, penalties, and the Receiving Party’s attorneys’ fees; or (b) that the other Party shall agree that the Receiving Party may grant the Disclosure Request without any liability by the Receiving Party to the other Party.

record_data.record_plain_text: The procedures set forth in this Section 11 shall apply in the event of a Significant Regulatory Change or a Significant Operational Change as described below. 11.1 Significant Regulatory Change A Significant Regulatory Change, as this term is used in this Section 11, shall be deemed to occur if FERC, the CPUC, the CAISO, DSOD, the Forest Service or any other agency or court having jurisdiction, the California Legislature, or the United States Congress issues an order or decision or adopts or modifies a tariff or filed contract or license, or makes a decision or enacts a law that significantly interferes with the ability of either Party to perform any of its obligations under this Agreement. 11.2 Significant Operational Change A Significant Operational Change, as this term is used in this Section 11, shall consist of any of the following: (i) either Party making a new interconnection of its Electric System with the Electric System of a Third Party, including any generation, which would have the potential for significantly affecting the operation of the other Party’s Electric System; (ii) installation or operation by either Party or a Third Party of a generation facility within a Party’s Electric System, where power or energy from such generation is intended to or may possibly flow through a Point of Interconnection and onto either Party’s Electric System; (iii) any other operational change proposed by a Party that could reasonably be expected to significantly affect the other Party’s Electric System; or (iv) an action taken by the Balancing Authority which may cause a significant change in the way a Party operates or must operate its Electric System or the Point of Interconnection between the Parties. 11.3 Change in Functions or Scope The Parties recognize that there may be a change in the functions performed by the CAISO or in the scope of the facilities under the operational control of the CAISO, or the replacement of the CAISO with a regional transmission organization that may perform different functions or have a different scope than the CAISO has, as of the Effective Date. Such a change shall not be deemed to be a Significant Regulatory Change unless the conditions described in Section 11.1 above are satisfied. Any transfer from PG&E to the CAISO of any functions contemplated in this Agreement can be a Significant Regulatory Change if the conditions described in Section 11.1 above are satisfied. 11.4 Notification At any time during the term of this Agreement, if either Party anticipates the occurrence of a Significant Regulatory Change or Significant Operational Change, and if such change may reasonably be expected to materially affect either or both Parties’ obligations or operations under this Agreement, such Party shall provide written notice to the other Party as soon as practicable, and in accordance with Section 30 of this Agreement. The notice shall contain a description of the change, including expected time schedules and of the effect of the significant change to that Party’s Electric System. If the Party giving notice believes that it will be necessary to amend this Agreement to address the anticipated change, then the notice to the other Party may include a proposal that the Parties meet in order to negotiate an appropriate amendment to this Agreement. The Parties shall promptly enter into good faith negotiations in an attempt to achieve a mutually agreeable modification to this Agreement to address any such significant change. 11.5 Amendment of Agreement If the Parties agree that an amendment to this Agreement is necessary to address a significant change, as discussed in this Section 11, the Parties will promptly proceed to negotiate such amendment. If the Parties have not reached agreement within 60 calendar days of the date of the first meeting, any unresolved issues shall be submitted for resolution through the dispute resolution procedures set forth in Section 23. After the 60 day period stated above, either Party may, but is not required to, unilaterally initiate an appropriate proceeding respecting this Agreement with FERC pursuant to Sections 205 or 206 of the FPA, which proceeding could include a request for modification of this Agreement to address the significant change, and the other Party may exercise its rights under the FPA to protest or oppose such filing. In the event of filing for termination, except in the case where PG&E anticipates a termination of its license for the Mokelumne River Project, PG&E, in coordination with KMPUD, shall make an appropriate regulatory filing of a replacement agreement such that the replacement agreement is effective contemporaneously with the termination date of this Agreement. If the Parties are unable to reach a mutual agreement regarding a replacement agreement, PG&E shall file with FERC a replacement agreement unilaterally. 11.6 Studies of Significant Operational Change If a Party receiving notice from the other Party of a Significant Operational Change believes that the proposed change may reasonably be expected to materially affect the operation of its Electric System, it may request a study of any such Significant Operational Change to determine the potential for any Adverse Impacts and any potential avoidance or mitigation measures thereto. The Parties shall cooperate in determining how the study should be conducted and providing information necessary to conduct such a study. If it is determined, based on the results of the study, that, in addition, a Facility Study or System Impact Study is required, such study shall be performed within the time and in the manner specified in the PG&E TO Tariff and as agreed by the Parties. All study Costs associated with a proposal for a Significant Operational Change shall be the responsibility of the Party whose proposal or actions will cause the Significant Operational Change. Any disputes over the necessity of particular studies or the Cost of such studies shall be resolved through the dispute resolution procedures set forth in Section 23. Upon completion of necessary studies, the Parties will each review the study results and discuss any recommendations for avoidance and/or mitigation of Adverse Impacts. 11.7 Mitigation and Costs Unless otherwise agreed by the Parties in writing, the Party whose proposal or action causes the Significant Operational Change (“Modifying Party”) shall be responsible for fully compensating the other Party (“Affected Party”) for the reasonable Cost, if any, of mitigating any Adverse Impact on the Affected Party’s Electric System caused by the change; provided, that such Costs may be paid by a responsible Third Party. Any reasonable Cost incurred by the Affected Party in its cooperation with the Modifying Party with respect to the Significant Operational Change shall be reimbursed by the Modifying Party. All avoidance or mitigation measures shall be completed before the Significant Operational Change is made. Any dispute regarding the need for, the nature of, or the Cost of mitigating Adverse Impacts or compensating the Affected Party for those Adverse Impacts that cannot be mitigated shall be resolved through the dispute resolution procedures set forth in Section 23. In the event changes in transmission delivery voltage, relocation of facilities serving Points of Interconnection or other changes in transmission facilities are necessary on PG&E’s side of any Point of Interconnection with KMPUD because of changes to PG&E’s Electric System consistent with Good Utility Practice or CAISO planning requirements, these changes shall be made by PG&E at its expense, unless the change is made at KMPUD’s request, for its benefit and at its sole discretion (in which case KMPUD shall pay the expense) unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Parties. For similar changes made to KMPUD’s side of the Point of Interconnection, such changes shall be at KMPUD’s expense unless the change is made for PG&E’s benefit and at PG&E’s sole discretion (in which case PG&E shall pay the expense) unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Parties. 11.8 Failure to Notify of Significant Operational Changes Each Party has a duty to provide advanced notice to the other Party of Significant Operational Changes planned for its Electric System that could reasonably be expected to have an Adverse Impact on the Electric System of the other. If a Party implements a Significant Operational Change without providing such notice, the affected Party shall have the right to open any affected Point of Interconnection if, in its judgment, it is necessary to protect the integrity of its Electric System, and the right to file with FERC under Sections 205 or 206 of the FPA seeking appropriate relief, including, but not limited to, amendment or termination of this Agreement.

record_data.record_plain_text: KMPUD is installing certain protection equipment in its KM Green Substation that it is deeding to PG&E via a Facilities Rearrangement Agreement, an example of which is attached hereto as Appendix B. In order for PG&E to be able to maintain and operate its equipment in KM Green Substation, within 90-days of the completion of KM Green Substation, the Parties will negotiate and execute an agreement that will provide PG&E access to KM Green Substation in order to allow for it to inspect, operate, maintain, repair and replace the PG&E equipment located in the substation. In addition to the protection equipment in KM Green Substation, where it is necessary for either Party to install any of its facilities on the other Party’s premises in order to accomplish the Interconnection or otherwise to perform the duties contemplated by this Agreement, the Parties hereby grant to each other, subject to any legal and regulatory requirements for any specific installation, for the term of this Agreement: (i) the right to make such installation along the mutually agreed route (subject to each Party’s right to protect its operations or that of its customers in its Service Area) of sufficient width to provide full legal clearance from all structures on such property; and (ii) access to each Party’s premises upon reasonable notice and at reasonable hours for any purposes reasonably connected with this Agreement. Neither Party shall be allowed or obligated to install facilities on the other Party’s premises unless and until all necessary licenses, permits, certificates, or other governmental authorizations or approvals that may be necessary are obtained and any necessary easements for the installation of facilities are granted. Electric facilities belonging to one Party that are installed on the other Party’s premises will be relocated only with the agreement of the owner of such facilities, which shall not be unreasonably withheld. The requesting Party shall pay the Cost, if any, of any such facility relocation. If such costs are FERC jurisdictional, PG&E shall request and obtain FERC acceptance to assess such costs prior to collection.

The Parties shall promptly enter into good faith negotiations in an attempt to achieve a mutually agreeable modification to this Agreement to address any such adverse determination. 16.2 Expansion of Obligations If, after the Effective Date of this Agreement, FERC or any other regulatory body, agency or court of competent jurisdiction orders or determines that this Agreement should be interpreted, modified, or significantly extended in such a manner that PG&E or KMPUD may be required to extend its obligations under this Agreement to a Third Party, or to incur significant new or different obligations to the other Party or to Third Parties not contemplated by this Agreement in a manner not anticipated by other agreements, then the Parties shall be relieved of their obligations to the extent lawful and necessary to eliminate the effect of that order or determination, and the Parties shall attempt to renegotiate in good faith the terms and conditions of the Agreement to restore the original balance of benefits and burdens contemplated by the Parties at the time this Agreement was made. 16.3 Renegotiations If, within three months after a determination, order or decision as described in Sections 16.1 and 16.2, the Parties either: (i) do not agree that a renegotiation is feasible or necessary; or (ii) the Parties cannot agree to amend or supersede this Agreement, then: (a) either Party may initiate dispute resolution in accordance with Section 23; or (b) PG&E may unilaterally file with FERC an amendment to this Agreement or a replacement agreement; or (c) KMPUD may take any action before the FERC or elsewhere which it deems appropriate.

record_data.record_plain_text: 2.1 Whereas, PG&E and KMPUD had previously executed a transmission interconnection agreement and transmission facilities agreement on July 17, 2013, filed together with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) as Service Agreement No 230 under PG&E’s Transmission Owner (“TO”) Tariff and permitted by FERC to become effective on August 1, 2013, which provided the terms and conditions of the interconnection between KMPUD and PG&E; and 2.2 Whereas, the Parties originally designed the interconnection such that PG&E would own the 115 kV tap line that KMPUD would build and deed to PG&E; 2.3 Whereas, the Parties now intend to pursue studies and redesign the project such that KMPUD will own the 115 kV tap line; and 2.4 Whereas, the Parties have now concluded that it would be mutually beneficial to terminate the original interconnection agreement and transmission facilities agreement under Service Agreement No. 230 and to enter into this replacement agreement and the associated transmission facilities agreement; and 2.5 Whereas, PG&E is registered with the North American Electric Reliability Corporation (“NERC”) as a Transmission Owner (“TO”), and as a Transmission Operator (“TOP”) in accordance with the NERC compliance registry process; and 2.6 Whereas, PG&E is a public utility providing both wholesale and retail electric power and energy sales and transmission and distribution services in northern and central California and owns an extensive electric transmission system within that area; and 2.7 Whereas, in 1998 PG&E became part of the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”), and operates within the CAISO Balancing Authority Area and transferred operational control of its transmission system under terms of the Transmission Control Agreement (“TCA”) to the CAISO; and 2.8 Whereas, PG&E is a Participating Transmission Owner (“TO”) and a party to the CAISO’s Transmission Control Agreement, under which PG&E is subject to the direction of the CAISO in the operation of its transmission system and under which the CAISO becomes the provider of transmission service over PG&E’s transmission system, pursuant to the terms of the CAISO Tariff, the PG&E TO Tariff, Transmission Control Agreement, Scheduling Coordinator Agreements, and Utility Distribution Company Operating Agreement, all of which enable PG&E to satisfy the obligations of operating within the CAISO’s Balancing Authority Area; and 2.9 Whereas, KMPUD is a municipal utility engaged in the distribution of electric power to customers located within the Service Area of KMPUD; and 2.10 Whereas, this Agreement is intended to provide for the terms and conditions of interconnections between the Electric Systems of the Parties; and 2.11 Whereas, the Parties agree to operate as two independent, interconnected electric utilities pursuant to the terms of this Agreement and in accordance with Good Utility Practice.

record_data.record_plain_text: Each Party’s facilities or control equipment at existing and proposed Points of Interconnection between the Parties shall be provided, operated, and maintained by each Party in a manner to ensure the safe and reliable operation of the Parties’ Electric Systems and in accordance with Good Utility Practice and the directives of a Party’s Balancing Authority. In the event that changes in delivery voltage, relocation of facilities, or other changes in facilities are necessary on one Party’s side of an Interconnection with the other Party because of changes on that first Party’s Electric System consistent with Good Utility Practice, such changes will be made by that first Party at its own expense. Corresponding changes on the other Party’s side of the Interconnection shall be at the other Party’s own expense. 7.1 Interconnection of KMPUD Facilities with PG&E's System For the purpose of this Section 7.1, PG&E’s Electric System consists of a combination of (i) transmission facilities that have been turned over to the operational control of the CAISO and are part of the CAISO Controlled Grid and (ii) other PG&E-owned facilities, including transmission facilities for generation ties or service to single customer substation and distribution facilities that have not been turned over to the operational control of the CAISO and are not part of the CAISO Controlled Grid. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed as either modifying, in any way, the applicable interconnection procedures included in the then-current versions of the CAISO Tariff, PG&E’s TO Tariff, or PG&E’s Wholesale Distribution Tariff or affording KMPUD or PG&E any special treatment, preferable or otherwise, with respect to those interconnection procedures. 7.2 No Power Export This Interconnection is being designed and implemented at KMPUD’s request, and solely to accommodate KMPUD’s request to establish a means for KMPUD to import power to meet its needs. The Parties agree that KMPUD must retain internal backup generation to meet its emergency and voltage regulation needs. These backup generators are not merchant plants that will export power to Third Parties. KMPUD shall not connect generating plants to its system with the intent to export such power to the CAISO controlled grid. Any generator interconnection to the KMPUD electrical system shall be for testing, emergency, or voltage regulation needs only, and shall comply with the then-current requirements of the PG&E Transmission Interconnection Handbook and its Appendices. 7.3 KMPUD's Facilities in the Mokelumne River Project Area PG&E currently operates the Mokelumne River Project under a license granted by FERC that terminates on September 30, 2031. The Mokelumne River Project includes the Dam, Salt Springs Power House and the right of way for a penstock between the two locations. The Salt Springs Power House contains two turbine generators with a total installed generating capacity of 43.5 MW. While not a Mokelumne River Project feature, PG&E currently has a 12 kV line within the Mokelumne River Project boundary. This line will continue to be operated and maintained by PG&E pursuant to the existing easement from the Forest Service. KMPUD will be responsible for acquiring a short-term special use permit from the Forest Service for the construction of the new alignment of the new 115 kV and 12 kV lines on Forest Service-managed lands. KMPUD will also be responsible for obtaining approval of its long-term special use permit for facilities it owns on land managed by the Forest Service. As of the filing date of this Agreement, this condition has been satisfied. When or if PG&E is no longer the license holder of the Mokelumne River Project, the Parties recognize that this Agreement shall be renegotiated. 7.3.1 KMPUD Cable Installation in the Dam This Agreement grants KMPUD permission to install its 34.5 kV cable in the Dam for as long as PG&E retains its Mokelumne River Project license from FERC. KMPUD installed its cable under the Dam roadway, except for the portion that crosses the spillway. Prior to any construction of this cable across the Dam, PG&E informed FERC and DSOD of KMPUD’s plans and gained approval. KMPUD’s 34.5 kV line will be embedded in the Dam using agreed-upon construction techniques. A pull-box, to facilitate installation and maintenance, was installed on either side of the Dam. KMPUD attached its 34.5 kV cable to the Dam spillway using the agreed-upon construction techniques. 7.3.2 KMPUD Maintenance of the Underground Cable KMPUD is solely responsible for maintaining and operating its underground 34.5 kV cable buried in the Dam and attached to the spillway. KMPUD shall coordinate all such maintenance with PG&E in advance of any work and shall make best efforts to ensure that the cable does not interfere with PG&E’s operation of the dam. 7.3.3 Raising the Dam KMPUD understands that PG&E is considering raising the Dam. In the event PG&E decides to proceed with this project, KMPUD will pay the incremental cost of relocating and protecting its underground 34.5 kV cable in the raised Dam and raising the aerial portion on the raised spillway structure. Such construction activities may result in extended outages of the KMPUD cable described in Section 7.3.1, for which PG&E bears no liability. KMPUD will be solely responsible for any Costs associated with constructing a temporary line or costs resulting from increased backup generator use. KMPUD will not attempt to block the raising of the Dam for reasons related to the cost of relocating the cable in the raised Dam. PG&E shall use its best efforts when designing and executing its plans to raise the Dam in a fashion that will avoid or mitigate the costs to KMPUD in protecting and relocating its cable. 7.3.4 Studies Related to Installing the 34.5 kV cable in the Dam KMPUD will be financially responsible for all studies, analysis, evaluations, etc. required by either PG&E or regulatory authorities related to the installation of KMPUD’s 34.5 kV cable in the Dam. PG&E will provide KMPUD an estimate of the cost of such studies and KMPUD will have the opportunity to comment on the scope or nature of the studies. Upon its approval of the study scope and cost estimates, KMPUD will promptly pay the estimated costs for such studies. Upon completion of the studies, PG&E will provide a summary of the actual study costs and a financial reconciliation will be performed, such that KMPUD will only be financially responsible for payment of actual study Costs. 7.4 Approvals Before Construction PG&E, DSOD, and FERC approvals are required for all designs, drawings and specifications prior to construction within the boundaries of the Mokelumne River Project, including those relating to the Dam, Salt Springs Switchyard and Tiger Creek Switchyard. KMPUD obtained all necessary authorizations from the Forest Service to make use of Forest Service lands prior to construction or installing facilities referenced in Sections 7.3 and 7.5. Each Party was responsible for applying for and acquiring all Forest Service special use permits associated with its ownership, operation and maintenance of facilities on Forest Service land. However, KMPUD will be required to facilitate PG&E’s efforts to obtain all necessary special use permits from the Forest Service for all PG&E construction activities. 7.5 Facilities between Salt Springs - Tiger Creek Line and Dam As currently contemplated, the Interconnection of the KMPUD Electric System with PG&E’s Electric System will require that the existing PG&E 12 kV line between the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek line and the Dam be replaced with two line sections as follows: (1) Between PG&E’s Salt Springs – Tiger Creek line and the new KMPUD KM Green substation. (a) A 115 kV pole line with 12 kV underbuild – This new line will extend from the KM Green Substation to a new 115 kV tap on the existing PG&E Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line. KMPUD will own the 115 kV pole line and PG&E will own the 12 kV under-build between the new tap point on the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line and the new KM Green Substation. Upon completion of the new 12 kV under-build line by KMPUD, KMPUD will install the new 12 kV service taps and cut-overs. Once the newly constructed 12 kV line is energized, KMPUD will remove and dispose of the existing 12 kV line, poles and related facilities. The 115 kV and 12 kV lines shall be designed by KMPUD based on the Facility Study and in accordance with PG&E specifications and standards. (b) A new 115 kV tap point with three (3) switches – This new tap point will facilitate the connection of the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line to the new KMPUD-owned 115 kV line. PG&E will design and construct a new 115 kV tap point with three (3) switches from the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line to KMPUD’s newly built 115 kV tap line. The tap point and three switches will be owned, operated, and maintained by PG&E. PG&E’s actual design and construction costs will be paid for by KMPUD. KMPUD will pay a Cost of Ownership charge for this tap point, as outlined in the associated TFA. KMPUD will own the new 115 kV line and PG&E will continue to own the newly relocated 12 kV line. The poles supporting the new 115 kV/12 kV line will be jointly-owned, operated and maintained in accordance with the rules and procedures adopted by the NCJPA. This jointly-owned pole segment will begin at the tap point on the Salt Springs-Tiger Creek 115 kV line and terminate at the KM Green Substation. (2) Between the new KM Green Substation and the Dam A 34.5 kV pole line with 12 kV under-build – KMPUD will design and construct a 34.5 kV pole line and a 12 kV under-build between the new KM Green Substation and the Dam. This line will be constructed adjacent to PG&E’s existing 12 kV line. The facilities shall be designed by KMPUD based on the Facility Study and in accordance with the PG&E specifications and standards. Upon completion of stringing the new 34.5 kV and 12 kV lines, KMPUD will install the new service taps and cut-overs on the poles. Upon completion of the new 34.5 kV/12kV line and service connections to the new line, KMPUD will, at its expense, remove and dispose of the existing 12 kV line, poles and related facilities. KMPUD will own the new 34.5 kV line and PG&E will own the new 12 kV line. The poles supporting the new 34.5 kV/12 kV line will be jointly-owned, operated and maintained in accordance with the rules and procedures adopted by the NCJPA. KMPUD agrees to maintain and continue its membership in the NCJPA. The jointly-owned pole segment will begin at the KM Green Substation and terminate near the Dam. KMPUD shall meet its NCJPA obligations relating to this line segment through its own staff or by contracting with other parties. In the event KMPUD’s 115 kV or 34.5 kV conductor(s) falls into PG&E 12 kV conductors, KMPUD shall be responsible for correcting this situation immediately. If KMPUD does not respond to such emergency condition in a reasonable amount of time, and in order to maintain service reliability to its customers, PG&E may clear KMPUD’s conductor from PG&E’s lines. PG&E will not be responsible to reconnect KMPUD’s conductor during such emergencies. (3) KM Green Substation The KM Green Substation will be designed, constructed and owned by KMPUD; however, PG&E will own and have access to the 115 kV line protection and telecommunication equipment at the substation (as described in more detail in Section 7.7). Upon completion of construction, KMPUD will deliver to PG&E, and PG&E will accept from KMPUD, a Facilities Rearrangement Agreement in substantially the form shown in Appendix B, attached hereto, conveying to PG&E ownership of the associated telecommunication and protection equipment in the KM Green Substation. 7.6 M&O of the Lines Between Point of Interconnection and the Dam Except as to any jointly-owned pole facilities that are governed by the terms and conditions of the joint pole agreement of the NCJPA, including the joint pole routine procedures, (a) KMPUD will be responsible for the operation, maintenance, repair and replacement of the 115 kV line between the Point of Interconnection and the KM Green Substation and the 34.5 kV line between the KM Green Substation and the Dam and all related costs; and (b) PG&E will be responsible for the operation, maintenance, repair and replacement of the 12 kV line between the Salt Springs Substation and the Dam and all related costs. 7.7 M&O of the KM Green Substation KMPUD will be responsible for the ownership, installation, maintenance, operation and, as necessary, repair and replacement of its KM Green Substation and the facilities contained therein, except that PG&E will own, operate, and maintain and, as necessary, repair and replace the 115 kV relays and related protection and telecommunication equipment, which is described in the associated TFA. KMPUD shall pay PG&E for PG&E’s costs to operate, maintain, repair and replace these KM Green Substation facilities through payments to PG&E as provided in the associated TFA. KMPUD shall provide PG&E with access to its substation for such work activities. The Parties shall execute an access agreement to memorialize this right of access. 7.8 Service to PG&E Customers Along the KMPUD 34.5 kV Line Neither Party will provide electric service from the new KMPUD 34.5 kV line to any customer in PG&E’s service area without an express written agreement between the Parties designating the Party to be service provider and addressing the responsibility for maintaining service to the new customer, indemnity and other terms and conditions as may be agreed to by the Parties.

record_data.record_plain_text: Pursuant to the CAISO Tariff, PG&E conducts planning studies of its Electric System annually to identify System Reinforcements or other modifications of its Electric System necessary to determine the Transfer Capability to reliably serve the expected loads connected to its Electric System including expected KMPUD loads at Point of Interconnection. 9.1 Planning Process In order for PG&E to include the effects of growth of KMPUD’s Electric System loads in its planning studies of the PG&E network supplying the Point of Interconnection, KMPUD shall provide PG&E with KMPUD’s electric load planning data by October 15 of each year. Such KMPUD electric load planning data shall contain the prior year’s actual peak load and the best estimate of KMPUD’s Electric System load for each year of the next five-year period being served at the Point of Interconnection. KMPUD’s prior year load data and five-year forecast shall be submitted to PG&E within 30 days of the Effective Date of this Agreement. PG&E agrees to keep KMPUD load forecast data confidential and will only use or share it with others when necessary for safe and reliable operations of the Interconnection except that such the information may be shared with the CAISO for any reason. In no event will PG&E share the information with PG&E marketing personnel or use the information for marketing or “load retention” purposes, and PG&E shall take such measures as are necessary to ensure that the information is used only for safe and reliable operations of the Interconnection except when the information is shared with the CAISO. In no event will PG&E use the information for any purpose that interferes with KMPUD’s utility functions, or that could alter or harm KMPUD’s relationship with its existing or prospective utility customers. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, a breach of the obligations to maintain confidentiality described in this paragraph may be remedied by resort to the California state courts, and KMPUD shall be entitled to seek legal and equitable relief with respect to any actual or threatened violation of these obligations. 9.2 System Reinforcements If, as a result of its annual planning review process, PG&E determines, through studies conducted pursuant to the CAISO Tariff and in accordance with the PG&E TO Tariff that a need exists to construct System Reinforcements that will have a direct effect on KMPUD, PG&E shall provide information including a description of the System Reinforcements and the schedule for construction or installation to KMPUD as soon as possible through a notice pursuant to Section 30. The Parties shall then follow the applicable procedures of the PG&E TO Tariff.

record_data.record_plain_text: The following terms, when used in this Agreement with the initial letters capitalized, other than proper names, whether in the singular, plural or possessive, shall have the meanings indicated below. 4.1 Accident Personal injury, death, property damage, or economic loss which: (a) is sustained by a Third Party, which is an ultimate use customer of a Party (“Claimant”); (b) arises out of delivery of, or curtailment of, or interruption to, electric service, including but not limited to abnormalities in frequency or voltage; and (c) results from either or both of the following: (i) acts or omissions relating to the engineering, design, construction, repair, supervision, inspection, testing, protection, operation, maintenance, replacement, reconstruction, use, or ownership of a Party’s Electric System; or (ii) the performance or non-performance of either Party’s obligations under this Agreement. 4.2 Adverse Impact An effect on a Coordinating Party’s Electric System resulting from a Modification, New Facility Addition, or Long-Term Change to Operations to the Primary Party’s Electric System that (1) materially degrades reliability of the Coordinating Party’s System or (2) materially reduces the ability of the Coordinating Party’s Electric System to physically transfer power into, out of, or within said Electric System. 4.3 Agreement This Interconnection Agreement between PG&E and KMPUD and its Appendices, as it may be amended. 4.4 Ancillary Services As defined in the Master Definitions Supplement to the CAISO Tariff. 4.5 Applicable Requirements Any applicable law or regulation; and any standards, procedures or requirements of an entity with lawful authority to control or govern, including planning, the applicable transmission system (whether in full or in part) or the Balancing Authority Area in which a Party’s Electric System is located, including but not limited to FERC, NERC, WECC, and a Balancing Authority. 4.6 Balancing Authority The responsible entity that integrates resource plans ahead of time, maintains load-interchange-generation balance within a Balancing Authority Area, and supports interconnection frequency in real time. KMPUD utilizes a Scheduling Coordinator, which schedules power and provides meter data to the CAISO. PG&E’s Balancing Authority is the CAISO. 4.7 Balancing Authority Area An Electric System (or combination of Electric Systems) to which a common automatic generation control scheme is applied in order to: (1) match, at all times, the demand of Electric System(s) within the CAISO Balancing Authority with the power output of the generating units within the Electric System(s), plus the energy purchased from entities outside the Electric System(s) within the CAISO Balancing Authority, minus energy sold to entities outside the Electric Systems within the CAISO Balancing Authority; (2) maintain scheduled interchange with other Balancing Authority Areas, within the limits of Good Utility Practice; (3) maintain the frequency of the electric power system(s) within reasonable limits in accordance with Good Utility Practice; and (4) provide sufficient generating capacity to maintain operating reserves in accordance with Good Utility Practice. 4.8 Balancing Authority Area Arrangements Arrangements between a Party and its Balancing Authority, or, if a Party is its own Balancing Authority, between a Party and WECC, in which the Party agrees to self-provide or procure the necessary resources and services and perform operations to meet Balancing Authority Area operating requirements and Applicable Requirements to maintain the operating reliability and integrity of the Balancing Authority Area’s electric power system(s) in an economic manner consistent with Good Utility Practice. 4.9 Business Day Monday through Friday, excluding federal holidays and the day after Thanksgiving Day. 4.10 CAISO Controlled Grid The system of transmission lines and associated facilities of all Participating TOs that have been transferred to the CAISO’s operational control. 4.11 CAISO Tariff The currently effective CAISO Tariff, on file at FERC as Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff, as it may be modified or superseded from time to time. 4.12 California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) The California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”), or its successor. 4.13 California Public Utilities Commission (“CPUC”) The California Public Utilities Commission (“CPUC”) or its regulatory successor. 4.14 Control Center KMPUD’s designated operations manager responsible for, among other things, its Electric System switching operations. 4.15 Coordinating Party The Party whose Electric System is or may be subject to an Adverse Impact as a result of a Modification, New Facility Addition, or Long-Term Change to Operations on the Electric System of the Primary Party. 4.16 Cost All just, reasonable, necessary and prudently incurred expenses or capital expenditures, including but not limited to those for operation, maintenance, engineering and facilities studies, Adverse Impact identification, Adverse Impact mitigation, contract modification, administrative and general expenses, taxes, depreciation, and fees for consultants, as determined in accordance with the FERC Uniform System of Accounts (if applicable to a Party) as such may be amended or superseded from time to time, and costs of capital. The appropriate components of the Cost, as defined herein, shall be applied for the particular transaction performed. 4.17 Dam The Lower Bear River Diversion Dam, which is owned by PG&E as part of the Mokelumne River Project license. 4.18 Direct Assignment Facilities Facilities or portions of facilities that are owned by PG&E and are necessary to physically and electrically interconnect KMPUD to the CAISO Controlled Grid at the Point of Interconnection. All Direct Assignment Facilities that are contemplated by the Parties as of the Effective Date of this Interconnection Agreement will be identified in a Transmission Facilities Agreement. 4.19 Division of Safety of Dams Department of Water Resources (“DSOD”) The California Department of Water Resources (“DSOD”) department charged with inspecting and insuring the safety of dams in California. 4.20 Effective Date The date specified as the Effective Date of this Agreement in Section 5.2 hereof. 4.21 Electric System All properties and other assets, now or hereafter existing, which are leased to, licensed to, owned by, or controlled by a single person or entity, and used for or directly associated with the generation, transmission, transformation, distribution, purchase or sale of electric power, including all additions, extensions, expansions, and improvements thereto. To the extent a person or entity is not the sole owner of an asset or property, only that person’s or that entity’s ownership interest in such asset or property shall be considered to be part of its Electric System. 4.22 Emergency or System Emergency An unplanned or unexpected operational event, series of operational events, or operational circumstance that: (1) causes, or is reasonably anticipated to cause, a sudden or immediate loss or interruption of an Electric System facility or any other electric generating or transmitting facility; and (2) in the judgment of the affected Party or its Balancing Authority, consistent with Good Utility Practice, requires the taking of immediate action, to (a) preserve, maintain, or reestablish the safety, reliability, integrity, or operability of the Balancing Authority Area, the Electric System or such other facilities as have been or will be affected; (b) avoid hazard to human health and safety or property; (c) minimize or avoid loss of load or the inability to furnish electric service; or (d) maintain the frequency or voltage within the Balancing Authority Area. Losses or interruptions resulting from regularly recurring or chronic operational or maintenance problems shall not be considered Emergencies. 4.23 Facility Study The PG&E report dated June 5, 2012 and titled “Facilities Study Report Kirkwood Meadows Public Utility District Proposed Electric Service with PG&E,” and any later facility study requested by KMPUD, upon completion of a System Impact Study, which facilities study is an engineering study that determines required or desired electric system modification(s), if any, to accommodate a new Point of Interconnection or a modification of an existing Point of Interconnection, including the cost and scheduled completion date for such modifications. 4.24 Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) or its regulatory successor. 4.25 Federal Power Act ("FPA") The Federal Power Act (“FPA”) as it may be amended. 4.26 Forced Outage Any full or partial outage of a Party’s transmission facilities that is caused by an Emergency. 4.27 Good Utility Practice Any of the practices, methods, and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts that, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety, and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather the practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region. 4.28 Interconnection The physical connection of PG&E’s Electric System and KMPUD’s Electric System that allows for the transmission of electrical energy by and between the PG&E Electric System and the KMPUD Electric System. 4.29 Interconnection Facilities Those physical facilities owned by KMPUD or PG&E that are necessary for the operation of the Interconnection. Interconnection Facilities include, but are not limited to, transmission lines, towers and supports, switching stations, buses, breakers, switches, relays, transducers, transformers, meters, protective equipment, communications and telemetry devices, and land and land rights associated with the Interconnection Facilities at each Interconnection. 4.30 Interconnection Service Where necessary, the construction of Interconnection Facilities and the on-going safe and reliable operation and maintenance of, and the Parties’ rights and responsibilities associated with, the relevant Interconnection Facilities. 4.31 KM Green Substation KMPUD ’s planned 115/34.5 kV substation, to be located between the Dam and Salt Springs Substation, approximately 1.3 miles north of PG&E’s Salt Springs Substation. 4.32 Long-Term Change to Operations Action intentionally taken, or an event permitted, by a Party that materially alters, on a long-term basis, the configuration or other operational characteristics of its Electric System. For purposes of this Section 4.32, an action or event shall be deemed to have been taken, or to have occurred on a long-term basis if the action or event remains in effect for a period of more than 30 consecutive days or occurred on more than 60 days within any period of twelve (12) consecutive months. The following are examples of actions and events that qualify as a Long-term Change to Operations when taken or occurring on a long-term basis, though this list is not exhaustive: (a) materially modifying a Remedial Action Scheme or disarming it contrary to the manner and conditions for which it is designed to operate; (b) opening switches that are generally kept closed under normal operating conditions, except in those cases where a modified switching configuration has been studied and agreed to by the Parties in accordance with Applicable Requirements; (c) closing switches that are generally kept open under normal operating conditions, except in those cases where a modified switching configuration has been studied and agreed to by the Parties in accordance with Applicable Requirements; (d) changes to ratings or operating limits of any element of a Party’s Electric System; (e) disabling or materially changing the operation of a phase-shifting transformer; (f) a significant load increase on a Party’s Electric System; or (g) action or events similar in nature and/or effect to the foregoing. A Long-Term Change to Operations does not include (i) outages taken for maintenance or Emergencies in accordance with Good Utility Practice, (ii) actions taken during maintenance or Emergencies to perform maintenance or respond to Emergencies, or (iii) actions taken by a Third Party, including the CAISO, that are beyond the control of the Parties. 4.33 Modification The removal of, or physical change to, any major element of either Party’s then currently existing Electric System, including any Primary Party or Third-Party generating facility, power control device, or electric transmission facility. 4.34 Network Upgrades Transmission facilities at or beyond the Point of Interconnection that are identified in a System Impact Study and/or Facility Study and utilized to relieve constraints on the CAISO Controlled Grid. 4.35 New Facility Addition The addition of a new transmission facility or the addition of a new generation facility directly connected to a Party’s Electric System, whether owned by that Party or not. 4.36 North American Electric Reliability Corporation (“NERC”) The North American Electric Reliability Corporation (“NERC”) or its successor. 4.37 Northern California Joint Pole Association (“NCJPA”) The Northern California Joint Pole Association (“NCJPA”) or its successor. 4.38 Participating TO As defined in the Master Definitions Supplement to the CAISO Tariff. 4.39 PG&E Transmission Owner (“TO”) Tariff PG&E’s Transmission Owner Tariff on file with the FERC as Electric Tariff Volume No. 5 as it may be modified from time to time. 4.40 Point Of Interconnection The physical connection of PG&E’s transmission or distribution lines with KMPUD’s Electric System. There is a single Point of Interconnection between PG&E’s Electric System and KMPUD’s Electric System, as of the Effective Date of this Agreement, at the newly installed 115 kV switch structure located on the existing Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line before the first newly installed 115 kV tap structure near PG&E’s Salt Springs Substation. Specifically, the Point of Interconnection will be the switch structure’s dead-end insulators supporting the KMPUD conductors identified on the attached “Drawing Exhibit 1”. This situation is contemplated to be the case only during the Interim Period defined in Section 5.4. Following the completion of the contemplated studies and future project, the Parties anticipate that the Point of Interconnection will be at a different location, which will be defined at that time. If KMPUD does not implement its future project in accordance with Section 5.4 during the Interim Period, the Point of Interconnection will be changed to the last structure of the 115 kV tap line from the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line to KM Green Substation, located approximately 1.3 miles north of PG&E’s Salt Springs Substation. 4.41 Primary Party A Party that proposes to make or makes a Modification, New Facility Addition, or Long-Term Change to Operations to its own Electric System. 4.42 Remedial Action Schemes (“RAS”) The automatic procedures that are required to maintain reliable operation of the Electric System after a disturbance on the interconnected Electric Systems. 4.43 Responsible Meter Party A Party having the responsibility for providing, installing, owning, operating, testing, servicing and maintaining meters and associated recording or telemetering equipment. Unless otherwise specified herein, KMPUD shall be the Responsible Meter Party under this Agreement. 4.44 Scheduling Coordinator As defined in the Master Definitions Supplement to the CAISO Tariff. 4.45 Service Area That area within the geographic boundaries of the areas electrically served at retail, now or in the future, by PG&E or by KMPUD. 4.46 System Impact Study An engineering study conducted by PG&E at KMPUD’s request and cost to determine System Reinforcements required on PG&E’s Electric System necessary to establish or modify a Point of Interconnection or to address a Significant Operational Change pursuant to Section 11. 4.47 System Reinforcements Reinforcements to PG&E’s Electric System, including but not limited to those identified by a System Impact Study, necessary to establish or maintain the Transfer Capability to a Point of Interconnection. System Reinforcements may be required when a Point of Interconnection is added or modified, when a Significant Operational Change pursuant to Section 11 is proposed, or when necessary to serve electric load reliably, or required by Good Utility Practice. System Reinforcements are limited to facilities required on PG&E’s Electric System and ordinarily would not include Interconnection Facilities required at the Point of Interconnection. 4.48 Third Party A person or entity other than PG&E or KMPUD. 4.49 Transfer Capability The measure of the capability of interconnected Electric Systems to move or transfer power in a reliable manner from one point to another over all transmission lines between those points under specified system conditions. 4.50 Transmission Interconnection Handbook (“TIH”) The PG&E Transmission Interconnection Handbook that PG&E has prepared, and that PG&E updates regularly, that provides technical requirements for transmission interconnections to PG&E’s Electric System. The most current version of the TIH can be found on the PG&E website at: http://www.pge.com/en/mybusiness/services/nonpge/electrictransmission/contractstariffs/handbook/index.page 4.51 Transmission Operations Center PG&E’s operations center from which it directs operations of its transmission system. 4.52 Transmission Owner (“TO”) As defined in the Master Definitions Supplement to the CAISO Tariff. 4.53 Transmission Owner (“TO”) Tariff PG&E’s Transmission Owner Tariff on file with the FERC as Electric Tariff Volume No. 5, as it may be modified from time to time. 4.54 Uncontrollable Force Any cause or causes beyond the control of a Party that renders the Party unable to perform an obligation, including, but not limited to, failure of or threat of failure of facilities caused by flood, earthquake, volcanic activity, tornado, tsunami, storm, drought, fire, pestilence, lightning and other natural catastrophes, epidemic, war, riot, civil disturbance or disobedience, vandalism, strike, labor dispute, labor or material shortage, sabotage, terrorism, road closure, governmental priorities or restraint by court order or public authority, and action or non-action by or inability to obtain or maintain in effect any necessary authorization or approval from any governmental agency or authority, which by the exercise of due diligence such Party could not reasonably have been expected to avoid and which by the exercise of due diligence it has been unable to overcome. Nothing contained in this Section 4.53 shall be construed as requiring a Party to settle any strike, lockout, or labor dispute in which it may be involved, or to accept any permit, certificate, or other authorization that contains conditions or terms the Party determines, in good faith, are unduly burdensome. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the term “Uncontrollable Force” shall not mean a Forced Outage. 4.55 United States Forest Service ("Forest Service") The United States department charged with managing the national forest. 4.56 Western Electricity Coordinating Council (“WECC”) The Western Electricity Coordinating Council (“WECC”) or its successor. 4.57 Wholesale Electric Power Requirements KMPUD’s entire electric capacity and energy requirements, including but not limited to related arrangements for transmission, Ancillary Services, or services which are similar, which are required by KMPUD to supply its load.
