record_data.record_plain_text: 5.1 Interconnected Operations This Agreement governs the relationship between PG&E’s Electric System and KMPUD’s Electric System wherein PG&E agrees to provide Interconnection Service involving the transfer of electric power at the Point of Interconnection by means of the interconnected and coordinated operation of PG&E’s Electric System (a portion of which has been turned over to the operational control of the CAISO) and KMPUD’s Electric System. The Parties agree that this Agreement shall relate exclusively to their rights and obligations pertaining to: (1) the Interconnection of their Electric Systems and PG&E’s provision of Interconnection Services to KMPUD, (2) the installation, operation and maintenance of the KMPUD 34.5 kV cable in the Dam, (3) the installation, operation and maintenance of the KMPUD-owned 34.5 kV pole line and a 12 kV under-build line on pole facilities that are jointly owned by the Parties between the proposed new KM Green Substation and the Dam, (4) during the Interim Period described in Section 5.4 (and continuing for the full term of this Agreement if KMPUD timely installs the corrective equipment in accordance with Section 5.4), the installation, operation, and maintenance of the KMPUD-owned 115 kV pole line and a 12 kV under-build line on pole facilities that are jointly owned by the Parties between the Salt Springs to Tiger Creek 115 kV line and the KM Green substation, and (5) the design and installation by KMPUD of 115 kV line protection and telecommunication equipment that will be deeded over to PG&E and located at the KM Green Substation. Under this Agreement, neither Party undertakes to provide or make available any Balancing Authority Area services, transmission service, distribution service, power or energy sales or services, or Ancillary Services for the other Party or any Third Party. At the Point of Interconnection covered by this Agreement, any transmission service on the PG&E Electric System from or to the Point of Interconnection covered by this Agreement, must be acquired from the CAISO and used in accordance with the CAISO Tariff and PG&E TO Tariff. 5.2 Effective Date This Agreement shall become effective (the “Effective Date” as used in this Agreement) on the later of (1) November 1, 2014, or (2) the date that FERC accepts this Agreement for filing and permits it to become effective. Upon execution of this Agreement by both Parties, PG&E will promptly file the Agreement with FERC for acceptance of the Agreement. This Agreement supersedes the original interconnection agreement between the Parties. 5.3 Conditions Precedent to Initiate Construction of Facilities Under the original interconnection agreement, the Parties agreed that construction of the Interconnection Facilities would not be constructed until four conditions precedent were satisfied. All four of the conditions precedents, listed below, have already been met. The Interconnection Facilities that were constructed are described in greater detail in the KMPUD Transmission Facilities Agreement (“TFA”), associated with this Agreement. 1) KMPUD joined the NCJPA, as described in Section 7.5 of this Agreement.; 2) The Forest Service issued the requisite short term special use permit to KMPUD for the construction of the new alignment of the 115 kV and 12 kV lines on Forest Service managed lands, as described in Sections 7.3 and 7.4.; 3) PG&E made application to the DSOD for authorization to install the 34.5 kV cable in the Dam and across the spillway as described in Section 7.3.1.; and 4) PG&E made application to FERC for approval of KMPUD’s facilities within the Mokelumne River Project boundaries. 5.4 Conditions Precedent to Commencement of Operations The Parties agreed that PG&E would not deliver electricity through the new Interconnection and the Parties would not commence interconnected operations under this Agreement until after the following two conditions precedent have been satisfied. Both these conditions precedent have been satisfied. 1) Forest Service issued the requisite long term special use permit to KMPUD, as described in Sections 7.3 and 7.4. 2) KMPUD entered into contracts or otherwise made satisfactory arrangements for meeting its Wholesale Electric Power Requirements, giving it the ability to operate as a utility within the Balancing Authority Area. 5.5 Interim Period of Operation During KMPUD’s Non-Compliance with TIH Requirements The current electrical protection system for the KMPUD-owned 115 kV tap line from Salt Springs to KM Green involves a three breaker system on a three terminal line; the three terminals are Salt Springs, Tiger Creek, and KM Green. PG&E is concerned that this configuration does not conform to the TIH requirement that the fault-interrupting equipment be located at the Point of Interconnection with PG&E, or as close to the Point of Interconnection as practicable—typically within one span of overhead line—and agrees with KMPUD that neither Party should depend on the other for the protection of its own equipment. PG&E agrees to give KMPUD a temporary and conditional waiver of the TIH requirements associated with requiring a close proximity between the line protection equipment and the point of interconnection in exchange for KMPUD’s agreement to remedy the condition and bring the 115 kV tap line in compliance with the TIH in a timely manner. Towards that end, PG&E agrees to grant KMPUD a reasonable period of time after the Effective Date of this Agreement to reconfigure and implement the project in a manner that will make it compliant with the relevant TIH requirements, based upon a schedule attached to this Agreement and labeled Appendix D (“Interim Period”). (a) During the Interim Period, KMPUD will own the 115 kV tap line that was constructed as part of the project. As a result, during the Interim Period, Income Tax Component of Contribution (“ITCC”) and Cost of Ownership charges associated with the 115kV tap line will not apply. (b) During this Interim Period, KMPUD agrees to indemnify PG&E for any and all liability or damages that are in any way associated with the operation and protection of KMPUD’s line, even if such liability or damage is a result of PG&E negligence, but excepting any liability caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of PG&E or as otherwise provided or limited by law. (c) During the Interim Period, KMPUD and PG&E shall rely on the existing facilities at the Tiger Creek, Salt Springs, and KM Green Substation for protection of the 115 kV tap line. (d) During the Interim period, the Parties have agreed that the study and project schedule described in Appendix D shall control, and that KMPUD must meet the deadlines and milestones described therein. However, KMPUD will be allowed an extension, if needed, due to delays caused by PG&E not completing required work according to the approved schedule. The length of the extension shall be commensurate with the period of time of the delay in PG&E completing the required work and the Parties will negotiate a reasonable extension of the Interim Period by amending Appendix D, as appropriate. (e) During the Interim Period, both Parties will work aggressively to design, obtain permits for, and install equipment as needed to ensure compliance with the relevant provisions of the TIH associated with requiring a close proximity between line protection equipment and the Point of Interconnection. During the Interim Period, both Parties shall utilize best management practices and due diligence in order to meet the study and project schedule shown in Appendix D. At PG&E’s discretion, the Parties shall meet at least quarterly to discuss KMPUD’s progress and the project schedule. (f) The Parties agree that a failure by KMPUD to meet a deadline or milestone described in Appendix D shall be considered a material breach of this Agreement and will permit PG&E to take the actions described in subsection (h) below and to terminate the terms and conditions of the Interim Period. However, the Parties acknowledge that KMPUD’s work could be delayed unexpectedly due to regulatory, environmental or other causes beyond KMPUD’s control. In the event of such a delay or for other good cause shown by KMPUD, and at PG&E’s sole discretion, the parties will negotiate a reasonable extension of the Interim Period by amending Appendix D as appropriate. (g) Pursuant to Section 11.6 and 11.7 (under which circumstances KMPUD will be considered the “Modifying Party”), KMPUD shall be required to pay the cost of all materials and work associated with the design, permitting and construction of line protection equipment and the relocation of the Interconnection Point in order to comply with the TIH. After installation or relocation by KMPUD of equipment associated with the redesign of the project to comply with the TIH, KMPUD and PG&E will amend this Agreement to (1) re-define and fix, for the duration of the Agreement, the Point of Interconnection, (2) confirm the responsibility for the operation and maintenance of equipment owned by each Party as described in this Agreement, and (3) recalculate the Costs of Ownership and ITCC tax charges that will be due from KMPUD. (h) To the extent that KMPUD fails to meet any of the deadlines or milestones described in Appendix D (including any amendments agreed upon by PG&E), PG&E, at its sole option, may elect to address KMPUD’s breach under sections 10.8 and 23 of the Agreement or PG&E may terminate the Interim Period and require KMPUD to deed over the 115 kV tap line to PG&E within five (5) business days, at which time all applicable ITCC charges would become due and payable by KMPUD and PG&E would commence levying Cost of Ownership charges associated with the 115 kV tap line. See TFA Exhibit A-2. A failure by KMPUD to deed over the 115 kV tap line to PG&E within five (5) business days of PG&E’s written demand shall be considered a material breach of the Agreement and will subject KMPUD to termination of the Agreement under Section 22, without the opportunity to cure. In the event that PG&E takes possession of the 115 kV tap line, KMPUD agrees to allow PG&E to make, and file at FERC, any necessary amendments to this Agreement to reflect the change in ownership and other consequences of PG&E’s termination of the Interim Period. 5. 6 Term and Termination This Agreement shall have a five year term, unless terminated early pursuant to Section 5.6.1 or renewed pursuant to Section 5.6.2. 5.6.1 Termination This Agreement shall terminate on: (i) the end of the twelfth (12th) month following the date on which either Party gives the other Party written notice that this Agreement shall be terminated, which notice shall not be given prior to the fourth (4th) anniversary of the Effective Date; (ii) the effective date of any termination pursuant to Section 8, (iii) the effective date of any termination pursuant to Section 10.7, or (iv) the effective date of any termination pursuant to Section 22. In the event that PG&E provides KMPUD with notice of its intent to terminate this Agreement, PG&E, in coordination with KMPUD, shall make an appropriate regulatory filing of a replacement agreement such that the replacement agreement is effective contemporaneously with the termination date of this Agreement. If the Parties are unable to reach a mutual agreement regarding a replacement agreement prior to the termination date of this Agreement, PG&E shall file with FERC a replacement agreement unilaterally. 5.6.2 Agreement Renewal and Renegotiation To the extent that PG&E remains the license holder of the Mokelumne River Project (as discussed in Section 7.3) and neither KMPUD nor PG&E has provided the other Party with notice of intent to terminate pursuant to Section 5.6.1, this Agreement shall automatically renew for a maximum of six five-year terms, for a total service period of 35 years, which includes the original 5 year term. In advance of each renewal period for another five-year term, PG&E and KMPUD will have the right to review the service arrangements and may propose changes to the service arrangements under this Agreement. Notwithstanding its renewal, the Agreement remains subject to termination pursuant to Section 5.6.1 above, except that any Party intending to terminate the renewed agreement pursuant to 5.6.1 (i) must provide the other Party with written notice of its intent to terminate the Agreement no sooner than the fourth (4th) year of any five-year renewal of the Agreement. As per Section 5.6.1(i), if notice is properly given, the Agreement shall terminate at the end of the twelfth (12th) month following the date on which either Party gives the other Party such written notice. The Parties will renegotiate this Agreement for any one of the following reasons: 1) Notification of a Significant Regulatory or Operational Change pursuant to Section 11.4; or 2) PG&E is no longer the Mokelumne River Project license holder as discussed in Section 7.3. 5.6.3 Post-Termination of Agreement Termination of this Agreement does not impact the rights and obligations related to KMPUD’s payment of Cost of Ownership charges related to the Direct Assignment Facilities, KMPUD’s 34.5 kV cable in PG&E’s Dam, KMPUD's 115 kV line and PG&E's 12 kV line, and KMPUD’s 34.5 kV conductor and PG&E’s 12 kV line. The jointly-owned poles supporting these conductors will continue to be governed by the joint pole agreement of the NCJPA. Each of these items must be addressed or included in future agreements except that if PG&E is no longer the license holder of the Mokelumne River Project (as discussed in Section 7.3), then KMPUD shall be responsible for obtaining all necessary authorizations, approvals, and use rights from the then-current license holder of the Mokelumne River Project, the owner of the Dam (if such owner is not the license holder), the Forest Service, and FERC.

record_data.record_plain_text: A.1 NEGOTIATION AND MEDIATION As provided in Section 23 of the Agreement, upon the failure of the Parties to resolve disputes between themselves, the Parties agree to seek settlement of all disputes arising under this Agreement by good faith negotiation before resorting to other methods of dispute resolution. In the event that negotiations between the Parties have failed, but before initiating arbitration proceedings under this Appendix A, the Parties may, by mutual assent, decide to seek resolution of a dispute through mediation. If this occurs, the Parties shall meet and confer to establish an appropriate timetable for mediation, to pick a mediator, and to decide on any other terms and conditions that will govern the mediation. If, after forty five (45) days from the date the Parties first met and conferred the Parties are unable to select a mediator and mediation date, and establish the terms and conditions controlling the mediation, either or both of the Parties may seek arbitration pursuant to Section A.3. A.2 TECHNICAL ARBITRATION The Parties agree that it is in the best interest of both Parties to seek expedited resolution of arbitrable disputes that are technical in nature. Technical disputes may include, without limitation, disputes centered on engineering issues involving technical planning studies and the need for and Cost of upgrade facilities. Such technical issues may be resolved through expert application of established technical knowledge and by reference to Good Utility Practice and industry standards. The Party initiating arbitration pursuant to Section A.3, below, shall indicate in its notice to the other Party whether it regards the dispute to be technical in nature. If both Parties agree that a dispute is technical in nature, then the Parties shall meet and confer to develop an appropriate timetable and process for expedited resolution of the dispute by a neutral expert, or ”technical arbitrator”. If the Parties cannot agree that a dispute is technical in nature, or if they cannot agree on a neutral arbitrator within thirty (30) days of first meeting and conferring, then either or both of the Parties may submit the dispute to arbitration under the procedures set forth in Section A.3. A.3 ARBITRATION A.3.1 Notices and Selection of Arbitrators In the event that a dispute is subject to arbitration under Section 23 of the Agreement and Section A.1 or A.2, the aggrieved Party may initiate arbitration by sending written notice (“Notice”) to the other Party. Such Notice shall describe the dispute to be arbitrated and identify the name and address of an impartial person to act as an arbitrator for the dispute. If either Party takes the position that the dispute is not arbitrable, either Party may take the dispute to FERC for resolution. Within ten (10) Business Days after receipt of Notice, the other Party shall, if it agrees that the decision is properly arbitrable, provide the aggrieved Party with a similar written notice (“Second Notice”) stating the name and address of a second impartial person to act as an arbitrator of the dispute. Within eight (8) Business Days of delivery of the Second Notice, each Party shall then submit to the two previously identified arbitrators a list of the names and addresses of at least three persons for use by the two named arbitrators in their selection of the third arbitrator. If the same name or names appear on both lists, the two named arbitrators shall appoint one of the persons named on both lists as the third arbitrator. If no name appears on both lists, the two named arbitrators shall select a third arbitrator from either list, or independently of either list. In any event, the two named arbitrators shall select a third arbitrator within twenty one (21) calendar days of receipt of the lists provided by each of the Parties. Each arbitrator selected under these procedures shall be a person experienced in the construction, design, operation or regulation of electric power transmission facilities, as applicable to the issue(s) in dispute. A.4 PROCEDURES Within fifteen (15) Business Days after the appointment of the third arbitrator, or on such other date to which the Parties may agree, the arbitrators shall discuss or correspond to determine the procedures that are to be followed in conducting the arbitration, including, without limitation, such procedures as may be necessary for the taking of discovery, giving testimony and submission of written arguments and briefs to the arbitrators. Unless otherwise mutually agreed by the Parties, the arbitrators shall determine such procedures based upon the purpose of the Parties in conducting an arbitration under Section 23 of the Agreement, specifically, the purpose of utilizing the least burdensome, least expensive and most expeditious dispute resolution procedures consistent with providing each Party with a fair and reasonable opportunity to be heard. If the arbitrators are unable unanimously to agree to the procedures to be used in the arbitration, the arbitration shall be governed by the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association. A.5 HEARING AND DECISION After giving the Parties due notice of hearing and a reasonable opportunity to be heard, the arbitrators shall hear the dispute(s) submitted for arbitration and shall render their decision within ninety (90) calendar days after appointment of the third arbitrator or such other date selected upon the mutual agreement of the Parties. The arbitrators’ decision shall be made in writing and signed by any two of the three arbitrators. The decision shall be final and binding upon the Parties subject to rights to appeal the decision to FERC. Judgment may be entered on the decision in any court of competent jurisdiction upon the application of either Party. A.6 EXPENSES Each Party shall bear its own Costs and the Costs and expenses of the arbitrators shall be borne equally by the Parties.

This agreement (“Agreement”) is made as of __________________ (“Effective Date”), by and between Kirkwood Meadows Public Utilities District (“KMPUD”), and Pacific Gas and Electric Company (“PG&E”), a California corporation. WHEREAS, KMPUD is constructing an interconnection with PG&E to be located in Amador County, California; and WHEREAS, KMPUD and PG&E have entered into an amended Interconnection Agreement, dated ____________2014, (“IA”); and WHEREAS, in accordance with the IA, KMPUD has constructed a 115 kV line from the Point of Interconnection to the KM Green Substation and a 34.5 kV line from the KM Green Substation to the Lower Bear River Dam; and WHEREAS, KMPUD has relocated PG&E’s 12 kV line, which was adjacent to KMPUD’s newly constructed 115 kV and 34.5 kV lines, pursuant to CPUC Rule 15, which remains in PG&E ownership, and WHEREAS, KMPUD has installed associated 115 kV line protection and telecommunication equipment at the KM Green Substation, collectively the “Facilities” and which are described in more detail in the attached Exhibit A of the this Agreement; and WHEREAS, in accordance with the terms and conditions of the IA, KMPUD intends to transfer said Facilities to PG&E along with payment of any payments required by the California Public Utilities Commission on donated capital; and WHEREAS, PG&E has agreed to own and maintain in good order said Facilities for the benefit of the public including KMPUD along with any necessary license from the U.S. Forest Service; and WHEREAS, through the Northern California Joint Pole Association, KMPUD will be responsible to maintain in good order, normal wear and tear and Acts of God accepted, the 115 kV line between the Point of Interconnection and the KM Green Substation and the 34.5 kV line between KM Green Substation and the Lower Bear River Dam; NOW, THEREFORE, the parties hereto hereby agree as follows: Definitions. All capitalized terms used, but not defined herein, shall have the meanings ascribed to such terms in the IA. Conveyance. KMPUD does hereby irrevocably and unconditionally convey, assign, transfer and deliver to PG&E all of its right, title and interests in and to the Facilities and PG&E hereby accepts such conveyance, assignment, transfer and delivery. Warranty of Title. KMPUD warrants that it has unencumbered personal property title to the Facilities and that, as of the Effective Date, there are no personal property liens on the Facilities, other than liens imposed for taxes not yet past due. KMPUD expressly warrants that it has the right to convey the Facilities with no further action or consents required. KMPUD warrants and hereby covenants, at its sole cost and expense, to defend PG&E's personal property title to the Facilities against all claims and demands of any person or entities whomsoever which may now exist or which may have accrued as of the Effective Date. KMPUD hereby agrees to indemnify and hold PG&E harmless from all liabilities, obligations, damages, causes of action, judgments, costs and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees) which PG&E may incur or suffer in connection with any breach by KMPUD of the warranties, representations or covenants set forth in this Agreement. PG&E acknowledges that the right to own, operate and maintain the 115 kV tap structure near Salt Springs Substation (the Point of Interconnection) with three (3) switches and 12 kV line components of the Facilities is subject to a U.S. Forest Service special use permit and that PG&E is responsible for maintaining the special use permit. Property Taxes. The parties hereto agree and acknowledge that as of the Effective Date, PG&E and its successors and assigns of the Facilities shall be responsible for and indemnify KMPUD and its affiliates, successors in interest and assigns against any property or similar taxes imposed on the Facilities (and any real property interests appurtenant or relating thereto) by any taxing authority. Successors-In-Interest. This Agreement shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the parties hereto and their respective heirs, representatives, successors, and assigns. Facsimile Signature; Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in two (2) or more counterparts (including by means of facsimile), each of which shall be deemed an original and all of which shall, taken together, be considered one and the same agreement. Governing Law and Jurisdiction. This Agreement shall be governed by, interpreted and enforced in accordance with the laws of the State of California, without giving effect to any conflicts of law principles. IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the parties hereto have caused this Agreement to be duly executed as of the day and year first set forth above. KIRKWOOD MEADOWS PUBLIC UTILITIES DISTRICT Print Name: Signature: Title: Date:
PACIFIC GAS AND ELECTRIC COMPANY Print Name: Signature: Title: Date:

TRANSMISSION FACILITIES AGREEMENT BETWEEN KIRKWOOD MEADOWS PUBLIC UTILITY DISTRICT AND PACIFIC GAS AND ELECTRIC COMPANY At the request of KIRKWOOD MEADOWS PUBLIC UTILITY DISTRICT (“Customer” or “KMPUD”), PACIFIC GAS AND ELECTRIC COMPANY (“PG&E”), a California corporation (collectively, “Parties”), agrees to furnish, at Customer’s expense, a new 115 kV tap point with three (3) switches from the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line to the new 115 kV tap line with 12 kV underbuild (as described in Section 7.5(1)(b) of the Interconnection Agreement between Pacific Gas and Electric Company and Kirkwood Meadows Public Utility District (“KMPUD IA”) that will connect the Customer’s KM Green Substation to PG&E’s Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line, described in Exhibit A attached to this Transmission Facilities Agreement (“TFA”). KMPUD installed the 115 kV pole line, with 12 kV underbuild, described in Exhibit A, between the new PG&E 115 kV tap point on the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line and KMPUD’s KM Green Substation. PG&E has been involved in the review and approval of the Customer’s design of the new steel poles and protection equipment. During an Interim Period defined in Section 5.5 of the KMPUD IA, KMPUD will own the 115 kV tap line and has committed to redesign the project and correct certain deficiencies related to the Point of Interconnection, such that KMPUD will bring the project in compliance with PG&E’s Transmission Interconnection Handbook in accordance with the terms of Section 5.5 of the KMPUD IA. However, if KMPUD does not implement this redesign during the Interim Period, as defined in Section 5.5 of the KMPUD IA, KMPUD will deed the KMPUD-installed 115 kV pole line, to PG&E. The Facilities have been constructed to provide Customer with a 115 kV connection from PG&E’s Salt Springs-Tiger Creek 115 kV line to the KM Green Substation, which will be located in Amador County, California, as described further in Exhibit A. This TFA, inclusive of its Exhibits, which are identified herein, is entered into pursuant to the KMPUD IA and is subject to all terms and conditions thereof. For purposes of interpreting this TFA, if any term or condition of this TFA conflicts with the KMPUD IA, this TFA shall govern. 1. KMPUD’s Interconnection Facilities KMPUD’s Interconnection Facilities shall consist of the following equipment, all of which will be owned by KMPUD: (a) KMPUD KM Green Substation and all equipment located within KMPUD’s KM Green Substation except as specifically noted below in Section 2(d); (b) A 115 kV steel pole line between the new 115 kV tap point with three (3) disconnect switches, on the Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line, and KMPUD’s new 115/34.5 kV, KM Green Substation; (c) Metering units and required communication and telemetry devices; and (d) Land and land rights associated with the location of such facilities. 2. PG&E’s Interconnection Facilities PG&E’s Interconnection Facilities consist of the following equipment, all of which will be owned, maintained, operated, repaired and replaced by PG&E: (a) A new 115 kV tap point from the new 115 kV tap line to PG&E’s Salt Springs – Tiger Creek 115 kV line (as described in Section 7.5(1)(b) of the KMPUD IA) with three (3) switches; (b) A 12 kV under-build line, between the new tap point to PG&E’s Salt Springs - Tiger Creek 115 kV line and the new KMPUD 115 kV KM Green substation and then to the Dam. This line will be designed and built by KMPUD. KMPUD will install the new service taps and cut-overs on the new 12 kV line; (c) Protection equipment in PG&E’s Salt Springs and Tiger Creek Substations; and (d) The relays in the KM Green Substation, including related protection and telecommunication equipment, which is currently contemplated to consist of: * 115 kV primary line relay – (current design is a GE-D60), * 115 kV backup line relay – (current design is a SEL-311C), * 115 kV power line carrier radio – (current design is a Pulsar UPLC), * 115 kV wave trap and tuning pack, * 115 kV line tuner, and * Remote Terminal Unit. Appendix C of the KMPUD IA is a schematic single-line diagram of the project and its various elements. It identifies each Party’s ownership of the project. 3. Engineering Agreement The Parties previously entered into an Engineering Agreement that was filed with FERC, in FERC Docket No. ER11-3914-000, accepted on August 26, 2011, as amended. The Engineering Agreement was terminated on August 1, 2013. This TFA incorporates all the costs and work that was performed under that Engineering Agreement. 4. This TFA includes and incorporates: (a) Exhibit A: Detail of Facilities Charges Exhibit A1: Description of Facilities describes the PG&E-owned Interconnection Facilities for which the charges in Exhibit A shall apply. Exhibit A-2: Description of Facilities describes the KMPUD-owned Interconnection Facilities that, pursuant to the project described in Section of 5.5 of the Interconnection Agreement, shall be reconfigured and implemented in a manner that will make it compliant with the PG&E’s Transmission Interconnection Handbook (“TIH”) requirements. During the Interim Period these project costs are excluded from the Cost of Ownership and ITCC. This information is being documented to memorialize the costs in the event KMPUD does not complete the contemplated project and the facilities are deeded to PG&E. Exhibit A may be revised or superseded by written agreement of the Parties. (b) Exhibit B: Sample Work Performance Agreement 5. Definition of “Facilities” and “Work” (a) “Facilities” are those facilities described in Exhibit A-1 to this TFA. The Parties agree that these facilities are required for the interconnection of Customer’s project with PG&E’s Electric System. All costs and charges identified and estimated in Exhibit A are subject to true-up and adjustment once actual costs have been determined. Future maintenance and operation costs for such Facilities will apply, and all such costs will be charged to and paid by Customer in the form of Cost of Ownership charges, as outlined in Sections 8 and 9 below. (b) For purposes of this TFA, “Work” is a specially-defined term, and defined in this subsection (b), only if Exhibit B, attached to this TFA, is completed, and applicable. At the current time, no such Work is anticipated. If such Work is required in the future, “Work” performed pursuant to a Work Performance Agreement consists of all work that PG&E performs as a contractor for the Customer at the Customer’s request. Such work may include moving, disconnecting or reconnecting existing facilities at Customer’s request and may also include furnishing equipment or facilities. All actual costs and charges incurred under a Work Performance Agreement are cost-based and final. 6. Customer shall pay PG&E, the amount set forth in Exhibit A, Section II, including an Initial Charge equal to the sum of the amounts identified in subsections A-G of Exhibit A, Section II, subject to true-up as provided in Sections 5 and 7 of this TFA. The Parties have agreed that, on an as-needed basis, PG&E will invoice KMPUD for all project-related costs and charges, and KMPUD shall pay all invoices in accordance with Section 14 of the KMPUD IA. 7. PG&E shall determine the actual cost of installing the Facilities and shall provide Customer a final accounting within one-hundred eighty (180) days of completion of the work identified in the Description of Facilities, attached hereto as Exhibit A-1. If the actual cost of the identified project is greater than the total amount that has been paid by Customer, then PG&E shall bill, and Customer shall pay for the remaining amount, including interest determined pursuant to Section 35.19(a) of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (FERC’s or Commission’s) Regulations, 18 CFR § 35.19(a). If the actual cost is less than the total amount that has been paid by Customer, then PG&E shall reimburse Customer the difference, including interest determined pursuant to Section 35.19(a) of FERC’s Regulations, 18 CFR § 35.19(a). 8. Where Customer has requested Facilities, Customer also shall pay PG&E any applicable monthly rates and charges, plus an ownership charge, as specified in Sections IV and V of Exhibit A to this TFA: Section IV: A Cost-of-Ownership Charge representing PG&E’s continuing monthly cost of financing (if PG&E has financed the facilities), owning, operating and maintaining Facilities; or Section V: An Equivalent One-Time Charge equal to the present value of the monthly Cost-of-Ownership Charge in perpetuity. The Cost-of-Ownership Charge shall commence on the date Facilities are first available for Customer’s use, as such date is established in PG&E’s records. PG&E will notify Customer, in writing, of such commencement date. The Equivalent One-Time Charge (if applicable) shall be payable by Customer to PG&E within 30 days from receipt of an invoice from PG&E. 9. The Cost-of-Ownership Charge for interconnections provided under this TFA is determined by PG&E in accordance with PG&E’s applicable percentage rates, which are calculated using PG&E’s most recent transmission owner revenue requirement on file with and accepted by FERC. PG&E charges the following Cost-of-Ownership rates for transmission facilities: Customer-financed, transmission-level rate = 0.38% of the project facilities costs monthly; and PG&E-financed, transmission-level rate = 1.20% of the project facilities costs monthly. Either Party may apply unilaterally for a change in rate pursuant to Section 31 of the KMPUD IA. 10. Where it is necessary to install Facilities on Customer’s premises, Customer hereby grants to PG&E: (a) The right to make such installation on Customer’s premises along the shortest practical route thereon with sufficient legal clearance from all structures above and below ground now or hereafter erected or installed on Customer’s premises; and (b) The right of ingress and egress from Customer’s premises at all reasonable hours for any purposes reasonably connected with the installation, operation and maintenance of Facilities. 11. When formal rights of way, easements or special use permits are required on or over Customer’s property or the property of third parties for the installation of Facilities, Customer agrees that PG&E shall use all reasonable efforts to obtain such rights of way, easements or special use permits, which shall be obtained at Customer’s expense or, if Customer and PG&E agree, Customer shall obtain any necessary permanent rights of way, easements or special use permits, satisfactory to and without cost to PG&E. 12. To the extent that modification is required of other agreements between Customer and PG&E regarding current or planned transmission projects in the vicinity of or impacted by the Facilities to be installed in connection with this TFA, Customer and PG&E shall make good faith efforts to agree on such modifications, recognizing that such modifications may be a necessary element of the overall scheme of generation and transmission facilities sought to be installed by PG&E and also recognizing that PG&E has already expended effort and costs to fulfill such other agreements. 13. PG&E shall not be responsible for any reasonable delay in completion of the installation of Facilities resulting from shortage of labor or materials, strike, labor disturbance, war, riot, weather conditions, governmental rule, regulation or order, including orders or judgments of any court or regulatory agency, delay in obtaining necessary rights of way, special use permits and easements, acts of God, delays resulting from PG&E’s responsibility to coordinate certain electric interconnections or modifications with the California Independent System Operator Corporation, or any other cause or condition beyond the control of PG&E. Moreover, PG&E shall not be liable for any direct, incidental, indirect, special, punitive, or consequential damages resulting from such delay. PG&E shall have the right, if for one of the above reasons it is unable to obtain materials or labor for all of its construction requirements, to allocate materials and labor to construction projects which it deems, in its sole discretion, most important to serve the needs of its customers, and any delay in construction, hereunder resulting from such allocation shall be deemed to be a cause beyond PG&E’s control. In any event, PG&E’s total liability for any delay in the completion of the installation of Facilities shall not exceed the Initial Charge already paid by Customer. 14. New electric extensions and connections, capacity upgrades to existing facilities, conduits and substructures, and the maintenance of facilities, conduits and substructures provided under this TFA shall be installed and made in accordance with fundamental design, installation, ownership, and maintenance provisions of Applicable Requirements and Good Utility Practice as defined in Sections 4.5 and 4.27, respectively, and as described in Section 7, General Interconnection Requirements, of the KMPUD IA. Interconnection facilities for Points of Interconnection at transmission voltage shall be installed and maintained in accordance with PG&E’s then-current Transmission Interconnection Handbook. All charges, payments and refunds shall be made solely under the provisions of this TFA. 15. If PG&E is prevented from completing the installation of Facilities for reasons beyond its reasonable control after twelve (12) months following the date of this TFA, PG&E shall have the right to supersede the applicable Exhibit or Exhibits to this TFA to reflect cost changes upon at least thirty (30) days’ written notice to Customer. Procurement Agreement for the Interconnection Project between Lathrop Irrigation District and Pacific Gas and Electric Company 1.0 INTRODUCTION Pursuant to the Federal Power Act and relevant Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) regulations, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (“PG&E”) provides interconnection services and studies for utilities desiring to interconnect to its grid. In connection with these services, Lathrop Irrigation District (“LID”) has asked PG&E to enter into this Procurement Agreement (“Agreement”) to procure materials for LID’s proposed interconnection of LID’s electric system to PG&E’s Kasson-Louise 60 kV line located in Lathrop, California (“Project”). 2.0 PROCUREMENT SERVICES PROVIDED BY PG&E This Agreement will enable LID to engage PG&E in providing procurement services (“Services”) for LID’s proposed Project prior to execution of a Transmission Interconnection Agreement, which PG&E and LID anticipate will take place in the third quarter of 2015. The initial scope of the Services relating to the Project shall be as follows: * Procure two new switches, 57 and 59, on the Kasson-Louise 60 kV line between Tower 18/135 and Tower 19/136, and one new additional switch 55 between tap point of new Tubular Steel Pole (“TSP”) A18/135A and LID’s Change of Ownership Pole. Estimated cost $175,000 * Procure new TSP (A18/135A) between Tower 18/135 and Tower 19/136. The new TSP will be able to carry the Schulte SW STA-Kasson-Manteca 115 kV Transmission Line, two One-Way SEECO Switches on the Kasson-Louise 60 kV and a Tap from the Kasson-Louise 60 kV Transmission Line. Estimated cost $55,000
* Procure New TSP (A18/135B) to accommodate the Kasson-Louise 60 kV Transmission Tap Line. The new TSP will carry a One-Way SEECO Switch; this One-Way Switch will have no angle deflection in any direction. Estimated cost $55,000 * Procure miscellaneous equipment including transformers (PTs) and conductor. Estimated cost $65,000 3.0 ESTIMATED COSTS FOR SERVICES PG&E estimates that it will cost approximately $350,000 to perform the Services (“Initial Estimate”). LID’s payment of the Initial Estimate shall be required after PG&E files this Agreement with FERC and obtains FERC’s approval or acceptance, as described in Section 5.0. In the event that PG&E reasonably determines that the actual costs are likely to be in excess of the Initial Estimate, PG&E shall notify LID as soon as reasonably possible of the revised estimated costs and shall not perform any Services that will cause PG&E to incur costs in excess of the Initial Estimate without first obtaining written authorization from LID to proceed. 4.0 OWNERSHIP OF PROJECT FACILITIES The facilities described in Section 2 relating to the Project will be procured by PG&E on behalf of and at the request of LID. LID’s payment for Services related to the Project will be capitalized with the other expenditures by PG&E related to the Project. If the Project proceeds to completion, as currently envisioned, ownership of all of the Project facilities will be memorialized in the anticipated Transmission Interconnection Agreement or in a transmission facilities agreement. 5.0 FERC FILING AND TERM This Agreement will be filed with FERC and become effective on the latter of (1) July 10th, 2015 or (2) the date FERC accepts this Agreement and permits it to become effective. PG&E will request a waiver so that it will be permitted to accept money on the date PG&E proposes this Agreement to become effective. Either party may terminate this Agreement with 30-days written notice. Once this Agreement has terminated for any reason, and accounting and payment for Services rendered is complete, PG&E will file a notice of termination of the Agreement at FERC. 6.0 PROJECT ACCOUNTING PG&E will provide LID with monthly invoices documenting the total costs incurred during the previous month. PG&E will attempt to notify LID at least 30 calendar days prior to the anticipated date that LID’s payment of the Initial Estimate (and any future payments) is exhausted based upon the aggregated costs of PG&E’s Services. With such notice, PG&E shall provide LID with an estimate of the additional funds necessary for PG&E to complete the Services. Within 30 calendar days of receiving such a notice, LID shall send PG&E the additional amount that PG&E estimates will be required to complete the Services (“Supplemental Payment”). If LID’s Supplemental Payment is not received within 30 days of PG&E’s notice, PG&E may, at its option, elect to halt Services under this Agreement until such payment is received. Once PG&E completes the Services, PG&E will refund any outstanding balance (if funds provided by LID are left unused) within 60 calendar days of completion of the Services. 7.0 LID’S RIGHT TO TERMINATE SERVICES Upon written notice to PG&E, LID may request that PG&E immediately stop providing the Services. Total costs incurred by PG&E up to the date such notice is received by PG&E will be summarized in a final statement. At such time, PG&E shall deduct this sum from any LID funds on hand prior to refunding the outstanding balance to LID. 8.0 WARRANTY OF SERVICES AND ASSUMPTIONS The Services will be based on specific assumptions and inputs either given to PG&E by LID or, if such assumptions are suggested by PG&E, they shall be agreed upon by LID.
